<Author>Exptrav
<Content>Not Recommended I went on a five-city tour of Italy and stayed at some of the best city hotels in the country. I decided to experiment with the self catering model at Residence Hilda for the first time, and am sad to say that i won' t be repeating the experiment again.First, the good: a very tasteful building with nice, modern and airy rooms. rooms were more spacious than hotels, and quite stylish. staff were very friendly. Initially, we were quite excited about the place.Now, the bad: TV was tiny, and a very complex satellite setup. I never could find CNN in the 2 days i was there. Reception couldn't help either. Then, there was no hot water for half of our stay. reception didn't tell us about the problem until my wife told me there was no hot water and I checked with reception. It took half a day, all night, and the next morning to fix, so we couldn't shower when convenient. Finally, you should know about the staffing model. This hotel has 1-2 people at reception, and cleaning ladies. That's it. You are essentially on your own. When we arrived it was lunchtime so we had to call reception on the mobile and wait 15 minutes for the person to come and open up the hotel front door.Now normally I wouldn't mind the small hassles because it is a self-catering hotel, and from now on I have a better idea what to expect. But to be fair, I don't think it is acceptable to pay over E300 per night for such a barebones experience. Not having hot water and paying E300 per night, and no offer of a rebate, is not cool. I would have been much happier had this hotel been priced at E150 per night. I got much ritzier 5 star experience at Principe da Savoia in Milan for example, for about the same money as Hilda. From a relative value perspective, Hilda just doesn't make sense unless you can get a room at a significant discount to 5 star full service hotels. 
